f
|f(x)| \le \frac C{1+x^2},\forall x \in \mathbb R, C>0
t \in \mathbb R
A(z)=\int_{- \infty}^{t} f(x)e^{-2\pi iz(x-t)}dx
B(z)=- \int_{t}^{\infty} f(x)e^{-2\pi iz(x-t)}dx
A(\xi) = B(\xi)
\forall \xi \in \mathbb R
F=\begin{cases} A,  & \text{in the closed upper half plane} \\ B, & \text{in the lower half plane}  \\ \end{cases}
|A(\xi)| = |B(\xi)|
C>0
t=0
t \in (-1,1)
A\not\equiv B
 f(x)=\begin{cases} 1+\frac{x}{2} & \text{ for }\, -2 \le x< 0\\ 1-x & \text{ for }\, 0\le x\le 1\\ 0     & \text{ otherwise } \end{cases}. 
 |f(x)|\le \frac{C}{1+x^2} \quad \forall x \in \mathbb{R}. 
